[src:vaadin-flow/getting-started] Get started building applications with Vaadin.
[src:vaadin-flow/getting-started] This guide will help you set up your environment, create your first Vaadin project, and take you through the essential steps of developing, running, and building your application.
[src:vaadin-flow/getting-started] Hit the ground running with Vaadin by creating a simple web application from scratch in this quick tutorial using only Java.
[src:vaadin-flow/getting-started] Get the most out of Vaadin by setting up your development environment with the right tools and configurations.
[src:vaadin-flow/getting-started] Learn about different ways to start a Vaadin project.
[src:vaadin-flow/getting-started] A comprehensive step-by-step tutorial to get started with Vaadin and learn best practices along the way.
[src:vaadin-flow/getting-started] Add features to your Vaadin project to turn it into a full-featured application.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Java gained popularity shortly after its release, and has been a popular programming language since then.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Java was the third most popular programming language in 2022 according to GitHub.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Although still widely popular, there has been a gradual decline in use of Java in recent years with other languages using JVM gaining popularity.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Java was designed by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] It was released in May 1995 as a core component of Sun's Java platform.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] The original and reference implementation Java compilers, virtual machines (VMs), and class libraries were released by Sun under proprietary licenses.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] As of May 2007, in compliance with the specifications of the Java Community Process, Sun had relicensed most of its Java technologies under the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Oracle, which bought Sun in 2010, offers its own HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] However, the official reference implementation is the OpenJDK JVM, which is open-source software used by most developers and is the default JVM for almost all Linux distributions.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] As of March 2026, Java 26 is the current version.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] James Gosling, Mike Sheridan, and Patrick Naughton initiated the Java language project in June 1991.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Java was originally designed for interactive television, but it was too advanced for the digital cable television industry at the time.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] The language was initially called *Oak* after an oak tree that stood outside Gosling's office.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Later the project went by the name *Green* and was finally renamed *Java*, from Java coffee, a type of coffee from Indonesia.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Gosling designed Java with a C/C++-style syntax that system and application programmers would find familiar.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Sun Microsystems released the first public implementation as Java 1.0 in 1996.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] It promised write once, run anywhere (WORA) functionality, providing no-cost run-times on popular platforms.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Fairly secure and featuring configurable security, it allowed network- and file-access restrictions.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Major web browsers soon incorporated the ability to run Java applets within web pages, and Java quickly became popular.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] The Java 1.0 compiler was re-written in Java by Arthur van Hoff to comply strictly with the Java 1.0 language specification.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] With the advent of Java 2 (released initially as J2SE 1.2 in December 1998 – 1999), new versions had multiple configurations built for different types of platforms.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] J2EE included technologies and APIs for enterprise applications typically run in server environments, while J2ME featured APIs optimized for mobile applications.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] In 2006, for marketing purposes, Sun renamed new J2 versions as *Java EE*, *Java ME*, and *Java SE*, respectively.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] In 1997, Sun Microsystems approached the ISO/IEC JTC 1 standards body and later the Ecma International to formalize Java, but it soon withdrew from the process.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Java remains a *de facto* standard, controlled through the Java Community Process.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] At one time, Sun made most of its Java implementations available without charge, despite their proprietary software status.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Sun generated revenue from Java through the selling of licenses for specialized products such as the Java Enterprise System.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] On November 13, 2006, Sun released much of its Java virtual machine (JVM) as free and open-source software (FOSS), under the terms of the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] On May 8, 2007, Sun finished the process, making all of its JVM's core code available under free software/open-source distribution terms, aside from a small portion of code to which Sun did not hold the copyright.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Sun's vice-president Rich Green said that Sun's ideal role with regard to Java was as an *evangelist*.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Following Oracle Corporation's acquisition of Sun Microsystems in 2009–10, Oracle has described itself as the steward of Java technology with a relentless commitment to fostering a community of participation and transparency.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] This did not prevent Oracle from filing a lawsuit against Google shortly after that for using Java inside the Android SDK (see the *Android* section).
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] On April 2, 2010, James Gosling resigned from Oracle.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] In January 2016, Oracle announced that Java run-time environments based on JDK 9 will discontinue the browser plugin.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Java software runs on most devices from laptops to data centers, game consoles to scientific supercomputers.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Oracle (and others) highly recommend uninstalling outdated and unsupported versions of Java, due to unresolved security issues in older versions.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] It must be architecture-neutral and portable.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] It must be interpreted, threaded, and dynamic.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] As of June 2026, Java 8, 11, 17, 21, and 25 are supported as long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Oracle released the last zero-cost public update for the legacy version Java 8 LTS in January 2019 for commercial use, although it will otherwise still support Java 8 with public updates for personal use indefinitely.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Other vendors such as Adoptium continue to offer free builds of OpenJDK's long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] These builds may include additional security patches and bug fixes.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Sun has defined and supports four editions of Java targeting different application environments and segmented many of its APIs so that they belong to one of the platforms.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] The classes in the Java APIs are organized into separate groups called packages.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Each package contains a set of related interfaces, classes, subpackages and exceptions.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Sun also provided an edition called Personal Java that has been superseded by later, standards-based Java ME configuration-profile pairings.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] One design goal of Java is portability, which means that programs written for the Java platform must run similarly on any combination of hardware and operating system with adequate run time support.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] This is achieved by compiling the Java language code to an intermediate representation called JVM bytecode, instead of directly to architecture-specific machine code.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] JVM bytecode instructions are analogous to machine code, but they are intended to be executed by a virtual machine (VM) written specifically for the host hardware.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] End-users commonly use a Java Runtime Environment (JRE) installed on their device for standalone Java applications or a web browser for Java applets.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Standard libraries provide a generic way to access host-specific features such as graphics, threading, and networking.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] The use of universal bytecode makes porting simple.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] However, the overhead of interpreting bytecode into machine instructions made interpreted programs almost always run more slowly than native executables.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Just-in-time (JIT) compilers that compile byte-codes to machine code during runtime were introduced from an early stage.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Java's Hotspot compiler is actually two compilers in one, with GraalVM (included in e.g.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Java 11, but removed as of Java 16) allowing tiered compilation.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Java itself is platform-independent and is adapted to the particular platform it is to run on by a Java virtual machine (JVM), which translates the JVM bytecode into the platform's machine language.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Programs written in Java have a reputation for being slower and requiring more memory than those written in C++.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] With Java 1.5, the performance was improved with the addition of the `java.util.concurrent` package, including lock-free implementations of the ConcurrentMaps and other multi-core collections, and it was improved further with Java 1.6.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Java uses an automatic garbage collector to manage memory in the object lifecycle.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] The programmer determines when objects are created, and the Java runtime is responsible for recovering the memory once objects are no longer in use.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Once no references to an object remain, the unreachable memory becomes eligible to be freed automatically by the garbage collector.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Something similar to a memory leak may still occur if a programmer's code holds a reference to an object that is no longer needed, typically when objects that are no longer needed are stored in containers that are still in use.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] If methods for a non-existent object are called, a null pointer exception is thrown.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] One of the ideas behind Java's automatic memory management model is that programmers can be spared the burden of having to perform manual memory management.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] In some languages, memory for the creation of objects is implicitly allocated on the stack or explicitly allocated and deallocated from the heap.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] In the latter case, the responsibility of managing memory resides with the programmer.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] If the program does not deallocate an object, a memory leak occurs.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] If the program attempts to access or deallocate memory that has already been deallocated, the result is undefined and difficult to predict, and the program is likely to become unstable or crash.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] This can be partially remedied by the use of smart pointers, but these add overhead and complexity.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Garbage collection does not prevent logical memory leaks, i.e. those where the memory is still referenced but never used.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Garbage collection may happen at any time.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Ideally, it will occur when a program is idle.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] It is guaranteed to be triggered if there is insufficient free memory on the heap to allocate a new object; this can cause a program to stall momentarily.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Explicit memory management is not possible in Java, however it is possible to make the JVM do garbage collection manually.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Java does not support C/C++ style pointer arithmetic, where object addresses can be arithmetically manipulated (e.g. by adding or subtracting an offset).
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] This allows the garbage collector to relocate referenced objects and ensures type safety and security.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] As in C++ and some other object-oriented languages, variables of Java's primitive data types are either stored directly in fields (for objects) or on the stack (for methods) rather than on the heap, as is commonly true for non-primitive data types (but see escape analysis).
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] This was a conscious decision by Java's designers for performance reasons.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Java contains multiple types of garbage collectors.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Since Java 9, HotSpot uses the Garbage First Garbage Collector (G1GC) as the default.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] However, there are also several other garbage collectors that can be used to manage the heap, such as the Z Garbage Collector (ZGC) introduced in Java 11, and Shenandoah GC, introduced in Java 12 but unavailable in Oracle-produced OpenJDK builds.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Shenandoah is instead available in third-party builds of OpenJDK, such as Eclipse Temurin.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] For most applications in Java, G1GC is sufficient.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] In prior versions of Java, such as Java 8, the Parallel Garbage Collector was used as the default garbage collector.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Having solved the memory management problem does not relieve the programmer of the burden of handling properly other kinds of resources, like network or database connections, file handles, etc., especially in the presence of exceptions.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] The syntax of Java is largely influenced by C++ and C.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, which combines the syntax for structured, generic, and object-oriented programming, Java was built almost exclusively as an object-oriented language.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] All code is written inside classes, and every data item is an object, with the exception of the primitive data types, (i.e. integers, floating-point numbers, boolean values, and characters), which are not objects for performance reasons.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, Java does not support operator overloading or multiple inheritance for classes, though multiple inheritance is supported for interfaces.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Java uses comments similar to those of C++.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] There are three different styles of comments: a single line style marked with two slashes (`//`), a multiple line style opened with `/*` and closed with `*/`, and the Javadoc commenting style opened with `/**` and closed with `*/`.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] The Javadoc style of commenting allows the user to run the Javadoc executable to create documentation for the program and can be read by some integrated development environments (IDEs) such as Eclipse to allow developers to access documentation within the IDE.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Java applets were programs embedded in other applications, mainly in web pages displayed in web browsers.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] The Java applet API was deprecated with the release of Java 9 in 2017.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Java servlet technology provides Web developers with a simple, consistent mechanism for extending the functionality of a Web server and for accessing existing business systems.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Servlets are server-side Java EE components that generate responses to requests from clients.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Most of the time, this means generating HTML pages in response to HTTP requests, although there are a number of other standard servlet classes available, for example for WebSocket communication.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Typical implementations of these APIs on Application Servers or Servlet Containers use a standard servlet for handling all interactions with the HTTP requests and responses that delegate to the web service methods for the actual business logic.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] JavaServer Pages (JSP) are server-side Java EE components that generate responses, typically HTML pages, to HTTP requests from clients.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] JSPs embed Java code in an HTML page by using the special delimiters `<%` and `%>`.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] A JSP is compiled to a Java *servlet*, a Java application in its own right, the first time it is accessed.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] After that, the generated servlet creates the response.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Swing is a graphical user interface library for the Java SE platform.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] It is possible to specify a different look and feel through the pluggable look and feel system of Swing.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Clones of Windows, GTK+, and Motif are supplied by Sun.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Apple also provides an Aqua look and feel for macOS.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Where prior implementations of these looks and feels may have been considered lacking, Swing in Java SE 6 addresses this problem by using more native GUI widget drawing routines of the underlying platforms.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] JavaFX is a software platform for creating and delivering desktop applications, as well as rich web applications that can run across a wide variety of devices.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] JavaFX is intended to replace Swing as the standard graphical user interface (GUI) library for Java SE, but since JDK 11 JavaFX has not been in the core JDK and is instead available as a separate module.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] JavaFX has support for desktop computers and web browsers on Microsoft Windows, Linux, and macOS.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] JavaFX does not have support for native OS look and feels.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] In 2004, generics were added to the Java language, as part of J2SE 5.0.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Prior to the introduction of generics, each variable declaration had to be of a specific type.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] For container classes, for example, this is a problem because there is no easy way to create a container that accepts only specific types of objects.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Either the container operates on all subtypes of a class or interface, usually `Object`, or a different container class has to be created for each contained class.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Generics allow compile-time type checking without having to create many container classes, each containing almost identical code.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] In addition to enabling more efficient code, certain runtime exceptions are prevented from occurring, by issuing compile-time errors.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] If Java prevented all runtime type errors (`ClassCastException`s) from occurring, it would be type safe.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] In 2016, the type system of Java was proven unsound in that it is possible to use generics to construct classes and methods that allow assignment of an instance of one class to a variable of another unrelated class.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Such code is accepted by the compiler, but fails at run time with a class cast exception.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Criticisms directed at Java include the implementation of generics, speed, the handling of unsigned numbers, the implementation of floating-point arithmetic, and a history of security vulnerabilities in the primary Java VM implementation HotSpot.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Developers have criticized the complexity and verbosity of the Java Persistence API (JPA), a standard part of Java EE.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] This has led to increased adoption of higher-level abstractions like Spring Data JPA, which aims to simplify database operations and reduce boilerplate code.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] The growing popularity of such frameworks suggests limitations in the standard JPA implementation's ease-of-use for modern Java development.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] The Java Class Library is the standard library, developed to support application development in Java.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] It is controlled by Oracle in cooperation with others through the Java Community Process program.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Companies or individuals participating in this process can influence the design and development of the APIs.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] This process has been a subject of controversy during the 2010s.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Javadoc is a comprehensive documentation system, created by Sun Microsystems.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] It provides developers with an organized system for documenting their code.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Javadoc comments have an extra asterisk at the beginning, i.e. the delimiters are `/**` and `*/`, whereas the normal multi-line comments in Java are delimited by `/*` and `*/`, and single-line comments start with `//`.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Oracle Corporation owns the official implementation of the Java SE platform, due to its acquisition of Sun Microsystems on January 27, 2010.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] This implementation is based on the original implementation of Java by Sun.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] The Oracle implementation is available for Windows, macOS, Linux, and Solaris.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Because Java lacks any formal standardization recognized by Ecma International, ISO/IEC, ANSI, or other third-party standards organizations, the Oracle implementation is the de facto standard.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Oracle has also released GraalVM, a high performance Java dynamic compiler and interpreter.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] OpenJDK is another Java SE implementation that is licensed under the GNU GPL.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] The implementation started when Sun began releasing the Java source code under the GPL.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] As of Java SE 7, OpenJDK is the official Java reference implementation.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] The goal of Java is to make all implementations of Java compatible.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Historically, Sun's trademark license for usage of the Java brand insists that all implementations be *compatible*.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] This resulted in a legal dispute with Microsoft after Sun claimed that the Microsoft implementation did not support Java remote method invocation (RMI) or Java Native Interface (JNI) and had added platform-specific features of their own.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Sun sued in 1997, and, in 2001, won a settlement of US$20 million, as well as a court order enforcing the terms of the license from Sun.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] As a result, Microsoft no longer ships Java with Windows.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Platform-independent Java is essential to Java EE, and an even more rigorous validation is required to certify an implementation.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] This environment enables portable server-side applications.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] The Java programming language requires the presence of a software platform in order for compiled programs to be executed.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Oracle supplies the Java platform for use with Java.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] The Android SDK is an alternative software platform, used primarily for developing Android applications with its own GUI system.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] The Java language is a key pillar in Android, an open source mobile operating system.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Although Android, built on the Linux kernel, is written largely in C, the Android SDK uses the Java language as the basis for Android applications but does not use any of its standard GUI, SE, ME or other established Java standards.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] The bytecode language supported by the Android SDK is incompatible with JVM bytecode and runs on its own virtual machine, optimized for low-memory devices such as smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Depending on the Android version, the bytecode is either interpreted by the Dalvik virtual machine or compiled into native code by the Android Runtime.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Android does not provide the full Java SE standard library, although the Android SDK does include an independent implementation of a large subset of it.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] It supports Java 6 and some Java 7 features, offering an implementation compatible with the standard library (Apache Harmony).
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] The use of Java-related technology in Android led to a legal dispute between Oracle and Google.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] On May 7, 2012, a San Francisco jury found that if APIs could be copyrighted, then Google had infringed Oracle's copyrights by the use of Java in Android devices.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] District Judge William Alsup ruled on May 31, 2012, that APIs cannot be copyrighted, but this was reversed by the United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit in May 2014.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] On May 26, 2016, the district court decided in favor of Google, ruling the copyright infringement of the Java API in Android constitutes fair use.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] In March 2018, this ruling was overturned by the Appeals Court, which sent down the case of determining the damages to federal court in San Francisco.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] Google filed a petition for writ of certiorari with the Supreme Court of the United States in January 2019 to challenge the two rulings that were made by the Appeals Court in Oracle's favor.
[src:vaadin-flow/java-programming-language] On April 5, 2021, the Court ruled 6–2 in Google's favor, that its use of Java APIs should be considered fair use.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] A **Rich Internet Application** (also known as a **rich web application**, **RIA** or **installable Internet application**) is a web application that has many of the characteristics of desktop application software.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] The concept is closely related to a single-page application, and may allow the user interactive features such as drag and drop, background menu, WYSIWYG editing, etc.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] The concept was first introduced in 2002 by Macromedia to describe Macromedia Flash MX product (which later became Adobe Flash).
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Throughout the 2000s, the term was generalized to describe browser-based applications developed with other competing browser plugin technologies including Java applets, and Microsoft Silverlight.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] With the deprecation of browser plugin interfaces and transition to standard HTML5 technologies, Rich Internet Applications were replaced with JavaScript web applications, including single-page applications and progressive web applications.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] In November 2011, there were a number of announcements that demonstrated a decline in demand for Rich Internet Application architectures based on browser plug-ins in order to favor HTML5 alternatives.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Adobe announced that Flash would no longer be produced for mobile or TV (refocusing its efforts on Adobe AIR).
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Pundits questioned its continued relevance even on the desktop and described it as "the beginning of the end".
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Research In Motion (RIM) announced that it would continue to develop Flash for the PlayBook, a decision questioned by some commentators.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Rumors stated that Microsoft was to abandon Silverlight after the upcoming release of version 5 -- this would later turn out to be the case.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] The combination of these announcements had some proclaiming it "the end of the line for browser plug-ins".
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] A **rich mobile application** (RMA) is a mobile application that inherits numerous properties from web applications and features several explicit properties, such as context awareness and ubiquity.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] After successful deployment of web applications to desktop computers and the increasing popularity of mobile devices, researchers brought these enhanced web application functionalities to the smartphone platform.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] NTT DoCoMo of Japan adopted Adobe Flash Lite in 2003 to enhance mobile applications' functionality.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] In 2008, Google brought Google Gears to Windows Mobile 5 and 6 devices to support platform-neutral mobile applications in offline mode.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Google Gears for mobile devices is a mobile browser extension for developing web applications enriched by a separate, user-installable add-on.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] These applications can be executed inside the mobile device with a web browser regardless of the architecture, operating system and technology.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] In April 2008, Microsoft introduced Microsoft Silverlight mobile to develop engaging, interactive UIs for mobile devices.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Silverlight is a .NET plug-in compatible with several mobile browsers that runs the Silverlight-enabled mobile apps.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Android accommodated the Google Gear plug-in in the Google Chrome Lite browser to improve the interaction experience of Android end-users.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Adobe Flash manipulated vector and raster graphics to provide animation of text, drawings, and still images.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] It supported bidirectional streaming of audio and video, and it could capture user input via mouse, keyboard, microphone, and camera.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Flash contained an object-oriented language called ActionScript and supported automation via the JavaScript Flash language (JSFL).
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Flash content could be displayed on various computer systems and devices, using Adobe Flash Player, which was available free of charge for common web browsers, some mobile phones and a few other electronic devices (using Flash Lite).
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Apache Flex, formerly Adobe Flex, is a software development kit (SDK) for the development and deployment of cross-platform RIAs based on the Adobe Flash platform.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Initially developed by Macromedia and then acquired by Adobe Systems, Flex was donated by Adobe to the Apache Software Foundation in 2011.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Adobe deprecated Flash in 2017, and the Adobe Flash Player was discontinued in most markets by early 2021.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Java applets were used to create interactive visualizations and to present video, three-dimensional objects and other media.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Java applets were appropriate for complex visualizations that required significant programming effort in a high level language or communications between applet and originating server.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] JavaFX is a software platform for creating and delivering RIAs that can run across a wide variety of connected devices.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] The current release (JavaFX 12, March 11, 2019) enables building applications for desktop, browser and mobile phones and comes with 3D support.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] TV set-top boxes, gaming consoles, Blu-ray players and other platforms are planned.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Java FX runs as plug-in Java applet or via Webstart.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Silverlight was proposed by Microsoft as another proprietary alternative.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] The technology has not been widely accepted and, for instance, lacks support on many mobile devices.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Some examples of application were video streaming for events including the 2008 Summer Olympics in Beijing, the 2010 Winter Olympics in Vancouver, and the 2008 conventions for both major political parties in the United States.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Silverlight was also used by Netflix for its instant video streaming service.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Silverlight is no longer under active development and is not supported in Microsoft Edge Legacy or newer.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] RIAs could use XForms to enhance their functionality.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Using XML and XSLT along with some XHTML, CSS and JavaScript can also be used to generate richer client side UI components like data tables that can be resorted locally on the client without going back to the server.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Mozilla and Internet Explorer browsers both support this.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] RIAs present indexing challenges to Web search engines, but Adobe Flash content is now at least partially indexable.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] Security can improve over that of application software (for example through use of sandboxes and automatic updates), but the extensions themselves remain subject to vulnerabilities and access is often much greater than that of native Web applications.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] For security purposes, most RIAs run their client portions within a special isolated area of the client desktop called a sandbox.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] The sandbox limits visibility and access to the file-system and to the operating system on the client to the application server on the other side of the connection.
[src:vaadin-flow/rich-web-application] This approach allows the client system to handle local activities, reformatting and so forth, thereby lowering the amount and frequency of client-server traffic, especially versus client-server implementations built around so-called thin clients.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripting is often used to provide a customized interface for the user.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] These scripts may assemble client characteristics for use in customizing the response based on those characteristics, the user's requirements, access rights, etc.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripting also enables the website owner to hide the source code that generates the interface, whereas, with client-side scripting, the user has access to all the code received by the client.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] A downside to the use of server-side scripting is that the client needs to make further requests over the network to the server in order to show new information to the user via the web browser.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] These requests can slow down the experience for the user, place more load on the server, and prevent the use of the application when the user is disconnected from the server.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] When the server serves data in a commonly used manner, for example, according to the HTTP or FTP protocols, users may have their choice of a number of client programs (most modern web browsers can request and receive data using both of those protocols).
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] In the case of more specialized applications, programmers may write their own server, client, and communications protocol, that can only be used with one another.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] Programs that run on a user's local computer without ever sending or receiving data over a network are not considered clients, and so the operations of such programs would not be considered client-side operations.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] Netscape introduced an implementation of JavaScript for server-side scripting with Netscape Enterprise Server, first released in December, 1994 (soon after releasing JavaScript for browsers).
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripting was later used in early 1996 by Fred Dufresne while developing the first website for Boston, MA television station WCVB.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] The technology is described in US patent 5835712 Archived 2020-02-25 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] The patent was issued in 1998 and is now owned by Open Invention Network (OIN).
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] In 2010, OIN named Fred DuFresne a "Distinguished Inventor" for his work on server-side scripting.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] In the earlier days of the web, server-side scripting was almost exclusively performed by using a combination of C programs, Perl scripts, and shell scripts using the Common Gateway Interface (CGI).
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] Those scripts were executed by the operating system, and the results were served back by the web server.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] Many modern web servers can directly execute on-line scripting languages such as ASP, JSP, Perl, PHP and Ruby either by the web server itself or via extension modules (e.g. mod_perl or mod_php) to the webserver.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] For example, WebDNA includes its own embedded database system.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] Either form of scripting (i.e., CGI or direct execution) can be used to build up complex multi-page sites, but direct execution usually results in less overhead because of the lower number of calls to external interpreters.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] Dynamic websites sometimes use custom web application servers, such as Glassfish, Plack and Python's "Base HTTP Server" library, although some may not consider this to be server-side scripting.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] When using dynamic web-based scripting techniques, developers must have a keen understanding of the logical, temporal, and physical separation between the client and the server.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] For a user's action to trigger the execution of server-side code, for example, a developer working with classic ASP must explicitly cause the user's browser to make a request back to the webserver.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripts are completely processed by the servers instead of clients.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] When clients request a page containing server-side scripts, the application server processes the scripts and returns an HTML page to the client.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] With the advent of single-page applications, an updated approach to server-side scripting was introduced, known as server-side rendering.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] With server-side rendering, static HTML can be sent from the server to the client, and client-side JavaScript then makes the web page dynamic by attaching event handlers to the HTML elements in a process called hydration.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] Examples of frameworks that support server-side rendering are Next.js, Nuxt.js, Angular.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] An alternative to server-side rendering is static site generation.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] With server-side rendering, the page is generally assembled on the server once per each request.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] By contrast, with static site generation, the application generates all the static HTML pages at build time.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] These pre-built pages are then sent to the client at each request, without having to build them again.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] This leads to faster rendering times, since a new page doesn't have to be generated on every request; the server simply hands over a file it already generated in the past.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] The downside is that when some data on the page changes, it needs to be rebuilt.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] Examples of static site generation tools are Jekyll and Gatsby.
[src:vaadin-flow/server-side-scripting] Sites generated by static site generation tools are often hosted on Netlify, Vercel or GitHub pages.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] Development began as the Millstone web framework in 2000.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] It was first released as open-source in 2002.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] Millstone introduced a component-oriented programming model for the web and an Ajax-based client communication and rendering engine.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] As a result, a large part of Vaadin's server-side API remains compatible with Millstone's Swing-like APIs.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] In early 2007 the product name was changed to IT Mill Toolkit and version 4 was released.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] It used a proprietary JavaScript Ajax-implementation for the client-side rendering, which made it rather complicated to implement new widgets.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] By the end of the year 2007 the proprietary client-side implementation was abandoned and GWT was integrated on top of the server-side components.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] At the same time, the product license was changed to the open source Apache License 2.0.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] The first production-ready release of IT Mill Toolkit 5 was made on March 4, 2009, after an over one year beta period.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] On September 11, 2008, it was publicly announced that Michael Widenius–the main author of the original version of MySQL–invested in IT Mill, the Finnish developer of Vaadin.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] The size of the investment is undisclosed.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] On May 20, 2009, IT Mill Toolkit changed its name to Vaadin Framework.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] The name originates from the Finnish word for doe, more precisely put, a female reindeer.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] It can also be translated from Finnish as "I insist".
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] In addition to the name change, a pre-release of version 6 along with a community website was launched.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] Later, IT Mill Ltd, the company behind the open source Vaadin Framework, changed its name to Vaadin Ltd.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] On March 30, 2010, Vaadin Directory was opened.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] It added a channel for distributing add-on components to the core Vaadin Framework, both for free or commercially.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] On launch date, there were 95 add-ons already available for download.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] Vaadin Flow's Java API includes classes such as `TextField`, `Button`, `ComboBox`, `Grid`, and many others that can be configured, styled, and added into layout objects instances of classes such as `VerticalLayout`, `HorizontalLayout`, `SplitLayout`, and others.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] Behaviour is implemented by adding listeners to events such as clicks, input value changes, and others.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] Views are created by custom Java classes that implement another UI component (custom or provided by the framework).
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] This view classes are annotated with `@Route` to expose them to the browser with a specific URL.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] Starting in October 2025, Hilla is being discontinued as a stand-alone product and merged into Flow.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] Vaadin includes a set of User Interface (UI) components implemented as Web Components.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] These components include a server-side Java API (Vaadin Flow) but can also be used directly in HTML documents as well.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] Vaadin's UI components work with mouse and touch events, can be customized with CSS, are compatible with WAI-ARIA, include keyboard and screen readers support, and support right-to-left languages.
[src:vaadin-flow/vaadin] To pass the certification, a developer should go through the documentation, follow the training videos, and take an online test.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] There are two parts to Custom Elements: autonomous custom elements and customized built-in elements.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] Autonomous custom elements are HTML elements that are entirely separated from native HTML elements; they are essentially built from the bottom up using the Custom Elements API.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] Customized built-in elements are elements that are built upon native HTML elements to reuse their functionality.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] The Shadow DOM is a functionality that allows the web browser to render DOM elements without putting them into the main document DOM tree.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] This creates a barrier between what the developer and the browser can reach; the developer cannot access the Shadow DOM in the same way they would with nested elements, while the browser can render and modify that code the same way it would with nested elements.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] The impact of CSS scoped within the Shadow DOM of a particular element is that HTML elements can be encapsulated without the risk of CSS styles leaking and affecting elements that they were not supposed to affect.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] Although these elements are encapsulated with regard to HTML and CSS, they can still fire events that can be picked up by other elements in the document.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] The scoped subtree in an element is called a shadow tree.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] The element the shadow tree is attached to is called a shadow host.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] A Shadow DOM must always be connected to an existing element, either through attaching it as a literal element or through scripting.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] In JavaScript, Shadow DOMs are attached to an element using `Element.attachShadow()`.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] An HTML template defines a block of HTML content that is not rendered when the page loads, but can be instantiated during runtime.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] Scripts within a template do not run, and resources are not fetched, until the content is cloned or added to the DOM.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] Web Components are supported by current versions of all major browsers.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] Backward compatibility with older browsers is implemented using JavaScript-based polyfills.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] There are many libraries that are built on Web Components with the aim of increasing the level of abstraction when creating custom elements.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] There are numerous community efforts for the Web Components ecosystem.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] WebComponents.org provides an interface to search for any existing Web Components.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] Custom Elements Everywhere validates whether popular front-end frameworks are compatible and ready to use Web Components standard, with a set of pending bugs and available workarounds.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] Moreover, Vaadin Tutorials has a dedicated section that shows how those workarounds are used efficiently with example demo apps and similarly related topics.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] In 2011, Web Components were introduced for the first time by Alex Russell at Fronteers Conference.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] In 2013, Polymer, a library based on Web Components was released by Google.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] Polymer is canonical implementation of Material Design for web application user interfaces.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] In 2016, RequireJS was introduced as JavaScript library and AMD loader plugin for custom elements.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] In 2017, Ionic (mobile app framework) team built StencilJS, a JavaScript compiler that generates Web Components.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] In 2018, Angular 6 introduced Angular Elements that lets you package your Angular components as custom web elements, which are part of the web components set of web platform APIs.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] In 2018, Firefox 63 enabled Web Components support by default and updated the developer tools to support them.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] In 2018, LitElement was developed by the Google Chrome team as part of larger Polymer project.
[src:vaadin-flow/web-components] LitElement was designed to be a lightweight and easy-to-use framework for creating web components.
